âœ¨1.Variables:

      import java.util.*;

      public class Variables {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
          int i = 26;
          String name = "Java";
          String str = name;

          System.out.println(i);
          System.out.println(name);
          System.out.println(str);
         }
      }

#### ğŸš€ What It Shows:
   âœ… import java.util.*; -> Imports all utility classes from the java.util package.
   âœ… public class Variables{ ->	Declares a public class named Variables.
   âœ… public static void main(String[] args) -> The entry point of any standalone Java application. It tells the JVM where to begin execution.
   âœ… int i = 26; -> Declares and initializes an integer variable i.
   âœ… String name = "Java"; -> Declares and initializes a String variable called name.
   âœ… String str = name; -> Creates a new String variable str and assigns it the value of name.
   âœ… System.out.println(...) -> method used to print output to the console.

ğŸ§®Output: 
              26
              Java
              Java
  

âœ¨2.Operators:
      import java.util.*; 
      public class Operators { 
        public static void main(String[] args) { 
          int a = 26; 
          int b = 21; 
          int ad = a+b; 
          int sub = a-b; 
          int mul = a*b; 
          int div = a/b; 

          System.out.println("Addition: "+ad); 
          System.out.println("Subtraction: "+sub); 
          System.out.println("Multiplication: "+mul); 
          System.out.println("Division: "+div); 
          } 
        }
      

#### ğŸš€ What It Shows:
  âœ… public class Operators ->	Defines the class where all operations will be handled.
  âœ… int a = 26, b = 21; -> 	Declares and initializes two integer variables.
  âœ… int ad = a + b;	-> Performs addition and stores the result.
  âœ… int sub = a - b; ->	Performs subtraction.
  âœ… int mul = a * b;	-> Multiplies a and b.
  âœ… int div = a / b;	-> Performs integer division. It truncates decimal parts.
  âœ… System.out.println(...)	-> Prints output to the console.

ğŸ§®Output: 
              Addition: 47
              Subtraction: 5
              Multiplication: 546
              Division: 1

âœ¨3.User Input:

      import java.util.Scanner;

      public class UserInput {
        public static void main(String[] args) {
          Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

          System.out.print("Enter an Integer: ");
          int a = sc.nextInt();
          sc.nextLine(); // Clear the buffer

          System.out.print("Enter Your Name: ");
          String Jaiii = sc.nextLine();

          System.out.println("You entered the Integer: " + a);
          System.out.println("You entered the Name: " + Jaiii);
          }
        }

#### ğŸš€ What It Shows:
  âœ…Scanner Class	Used to capture user input via console
  âœ…sc.nextInt() -> 	Reads an integer from user
  âœ…sc.nextLine() ->	Reads a string and clears newline buffer
  âœ…System.out.print() -> 	Prompts the user
  âœ…System.out.println() -> 	Displays output

ğŸ§®Output: 

                Enter an Integer: 24
                Enter Your Name: Jayanthi

                You entered the Integer: 24
                You entered the Name: Jayanthi


      
